ian Magazine''|work=Volume 6|location=Philadelphia|publisher=Printed for the Proprietors, by William Young, Bookseller, No. 52, Second street, the corner of Chesnut\u2014street|lccn=sn98034230|oclc=50655818|accessdate=2019-09-23|via=[[Internet Archive]]}}\n::(1) Pages 222&ndash;224 (October 1792): {{cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/universalasylum21792phil/page/222|title=Letter from the famous self-taught astronomer, Benjamin Banneker, a black man, to Thomas Jefferson, Esq., Secretary of State.|location=Maryland, Baltimore county, near Ellicott's Lower Mills|date=1791-08-19|accessdate=2019-09-23|via=[[Internet Archive]]}}\n::(2) Page 224 (October 1792): {{cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/universalasylum21792phil/page/224|title=Mr. Jefferson's answer to the preceding letter.|location=Philadelphia|date=1791-08-30|accessdate=2019-09-23|via=[[Internet Archive]]}} \n* {{cite book|last=Banneker|first=Benjamin|url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=uiug.30112037299119;view=1up;seq=57|title=Banneker's almanac, for the year 1795: Being the Third After Leap Year: Containing, (besides every thing necessary in an almanac,) an Account of the Yellow Fever, lately prevalent in Philadelphia, with the Number of those who died, from the First of August till the Ninth of November, 1793|year=1794|location=Philadelphia|publisher=Printed for William Young, Bookseller, no. 52, the Corner of Chesnut and Second\u2014streets|oclc=62824552}} ''In'' {{cite book|url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=uiug.30112037299119;view=1up;seq=5|title=Banneker's Almanack and Ephemeris for the Year of Our Lord 1793; being The First After Bisixtile or Leap Year and Bannekeer's Almanac, For the Year 1795, Being the Third After Leap Year: Afro-American History Series: Rhistoric Publication No. 202 (1969 Reprint Edition)|editor=Whiteman, Maxwell|publisher=Rhistoric Publications, a division of Microsurance Inc.|lccn=72077039|oclc=907004619|accessdate=2017-06-14|via=[[HathiTrust|HathiTrus