hp?question=1 |archivedate=December 1, 2008 }}. Cited in Rosenberger, Phillip (2011). ''Juggling Basics, Why and How To''.<!--unpaginated--> {{ISBN|9780983339700}}.</ref> Thus tricks such as the one ball cascade toss back and forth, 300,<ref name=\"Examples\">Darley, Vincent (1996). \"[http://www.juggling.org/help/siteswap/examples.html Site Swaps: Examples]\", ''Juggling.org''. Accessed: October 24, 2016.</ref> for example, may not be considered valid patterns. Throws back and forth shower style, odd numbers, are the most common one prop practice. Invalid or practice patterns and tricks are marked with an X.\n\nThe numbers are as follows:<ref>\"[https://www.bbc.com/news/magazine-20728493 Juggling by numbers: How notation revealed new tricks]\", ''BBC.com'' (BBC article with explanatory video)</ref>\n*0 = \"missing\"/rest [empty hand]\n*1 = pass [between hands]\n*2 = hold [one hand/no toss]\n*3 = (3-ball) cascade toss [between hands]\n*4 = (4-ball) fountain or columns toss [up and into same hand]\n*5 = high toss [between hands]\n*...\n*a = 10 = high columns/fountain toss\n*...\n\nSymbols:\n{{Div col}}\n*Number: Relative height of a toss. 1, 2, 3...\n*Brackets []: Multiplex. [333]33.\n*Chevrons and vertical bar <|>: Simultaneous and passing patterns.\n**P: Pass. <333P|333P>\n**Fraction: Pass 1/y beats later. <4.5 3 3 | 3 4 3.5>\n*Parentheses (): Synchronous pattern.\n** *: Synchronous pattern that switches sides. (4,2x)(2x,4) = (4,2x)*\n**x: Toss to the other hand during a synchronous pattern.\n{{Div col end}}\n\n==Asynchronous==\n{{hidden|1=Animations|ta1=right|multiline=y|2={{multiple image\n | align = \n | direction = vertical\n | width = 100\n | image1 = Siteswap 3b 531.gif\n | caption1 = 531\n | image3 = 5-ball cascade movie.gif\n | caption3 = Cascade: 5\n | image4 = Malabarismo con 7 pelotas.gif\n | caption4 = Cascade: 7\n}}}}\n\nA pattern is symmetrical (S) if both hands play the same role and asymmetrical (A) if not. All asynchronous patterns whose periods are odd are symmetrical, and all asynchronous patterns whose periods are even are asymmetrical.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size:100%;text-align:center;\"\n|+ Juggling patterns by siteswap\n! Siteswap || Name || Props || Period || Symmetry<br/> (S/A)\n|-\n| {{right|0}}X || Empty hand || 0 || 1 || S\n|-\n| {{right|1}}X || Direct toss to other hand || 1 || 1 || S\n|-\n| {{right|2}}X || Holding a prop in each hand || 2 || 1 || S\n|-\n| {{right|3}} || [[Cascade (juggling)|Cascade]],<ref name=\"Examples\"/><ref name=\"Orgfaq\"/><ref name=\"Phillips\"/><ref>{{Library of Juggling|balls=3|id=Cascade|title=Cascade|access-date=October 24, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Jugglinglab\">\"[http://jugglinglab.sourceforge.net/html/ssnotation.html Siteswap notation]\", ''JugglingLab''. Accessed: October 24, 2016.</ref><ref name=\"Burns\">Burns, Aiden. \"[http://geocities.ws/aidanjburns/notations.pdf Notations: Ladder Diagrams]\", p.11. ''Aidan's Juggling Page''. Accessed: 11 10 2016.</ref><ref name=\"Posets\">{{cite book |chapter=Juggling Patterns, Passing, and Posets|title=Mathematical Adventures for Students and Amateurs |editor-last1=Hayes |editor-first1=David F. |editor-last2=Shubin |editor-first2=Tatiana |last1=Buhler |first1=Joe |last2=Graham |first2=Ron |year=2004 |publisher=The Mathematical Association of America |location= |isbn=0-88385-548-8 |pages=100\u20131 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PD0clAlF8O4C&pg=PA99&lpg=PA99&dq=%22Paul+Klimek%22+siteswaps#v=onepage&q&f=false |accessdate=February 17, 2011 }}</ref> <br/> reverse cascade,<ref>{{Library of Juggling|balls=3|id=ReverseCascade|title=Reverse Cascade|access-date=October 24, 2016}}</ref> [[:Category:Siteswap 3|etc.]]<ref>\"[https://www.twjc.co.uk/tut046.html Statue of Liberty]\", ''Tunbridge Wells Juggling Club''.</ref><ref>\"[http://www.libraryofjuggling.com/Tricks/3balltricks/MillsMess.html Mills Mess]\", \"[http://www.libraryofjuggling.com/Tricks/3balltricks/ReverseMillsMess.html Reverse Mills Mess]\